REQUIREMENTS -----------------------------------------------------------

The GNU Scientific Library (http://www.gnu.org/software/gsl).
For instance, in a Fedora Core Linux system you can install it using yum:

# yum install gsl gsl-devel

Other required packages: xorg-x11-devel freeglut-devel

INSTALLATION -----------------------------------------------------------

$ runhaskell Setup.hs configure --prefix=$HOME
$ runhaskell Setup.hs build
$ runhaskell Setup.hs install --user

(You should also repeat these steps after a darcs pull.)

These commands and a few tests can be also invoked by the script:

$ ./setup

NOTE: The library should be used from another directory.
For instance, to run the examples:

$ cd examples

Interactive:

$ ghci demo.hs
> main

Script:

$ runhaskell demo.hs

Compiled:

$ ghc --make demo.hs -o demo

If --make is not given we need -package GSL:

$ ghc demo.hs -o demo -package GSL

USING ATLAS OPTIMIZED LIBRARIES ----------------------------------------

The performance of some linear algebra computations with big matrices 
significantly increases using ATLAS (http://math-atlas.sourceforge.net/).

In Fedora Core >= 4 you can install it using yum: 

# yum install atlas

or better:

# yum install octave

which includes other useful packages such as atlas, fftw, gnuplot, etc.

(You can also download precompiled atlas libraries from https://sourceforge.net/project/showfiles.php?group_id=23725)

To use the atlas cblas library you can simply 
include it in the command line:

$ ghc --make pca1.hs /usr/lib/atlas/libcblas.so.3

Another possibility is to change the following line in GSLHaskell.cabal:

- extra-libraries:    gsl gslcblas
+ extra-libraries:    gsl cblas

and reinstall the library.

(But in this case, in Fedora Core 4 I need a symbolic link:
root# ln -s /usr/lib/atlas/libcblas.so.3 /usr/local/lib/libcblas.so
)

